TC, you and (I think) Bob are somewhat missing the point. The reason
Newt would want to debate Hillary is because she is the only Democrat
candidate bright enough (and perhaps foolish enough) to meaningfully
engage him on the real issues. Much of the public is too ignorant to
follow such a discussion directly, but would be able to discern the
victor of such a debate by the demeanor of the combatants. (Hillary's
short fuse would be an advantage here, as well.) In such a debate, some
light might just be generated along with all the predictable heat.

I don't think you are so much a conservative as you are a proponent of
the right wing stance on a number of the largely unimportant issues,
issues which persist primarily because they are useful for inflaming the
bases of both parties. Most of the points you and Bob discuss in this
thread are important only to the extent that they motivate the simple
minded or ill-educated to back one party or another. For example, global
warming: even if it is a fraud or vastly exaggerated, which I believe it
is, we should still be pursuing *rational* solutions to energy
production/ conservation for economic and foreign policy reasons. As
long as we lack a rational energy strategy, global warming/cooling/
drying/wetting/etc. will remain a political lever too powerful to
discard and little or nothing will be done to address the real energy
issues. Another example would be Roe v Wade: overturning that case would
have no effect in 39 or 50 states, likely fewer, as state governments in
most of the remaining 11 would make immediate changes to grant the same
abortion rights Ronald Reagan signed into law as Governor of California.

The real problems our country faces are degenerative and systemic. The
system of government created by our founders was to have a strong
bicameral legislature, a weak judiciary, and an executive which is weak
except in times of war. (It is no accident that war is declared by
congress but the tools for achieving the peace are largely vested in the
executive.) Since Marbury v Madison (1803), the judiciary has gradually
usurped power from the legislature, a process which continues to this
day. Congress, in turn, usurps power from the individual states with
tacit (and occasionally active) support from the federal courts, which,
in their turn, usurp those new powers unto themselves.

The net result is a very strong federal judiciary and a weak
legislature, empowered only to rob the public in a continuing quest to
perpetuate itself. The executive, regardless of the party affiliation,
is largely ineffective except around the margins. It is a system
guaranteed to foster the corruption we witness.

The only real solution is a rethink of our &quot;living Constitution.&quot; Step
one, put a stake through its heart and kill it dead (Scalia, &quot;I like my
Constitution dead.&quot;) Amend the Constitution to severely limit the power
of the Supreme Court. Step two, amend the 14th amendment and restore
*some* power to the individual states. Amend the 16th amendment to limit
the power of Congress to perform the sort of mischief it does by
limiting both the size of the purse and the purposes to which its
contents can be put.

Since none of the proposed changes are likely, we're pretty much
buggered. This leaves the rational voter only one choice, hold your nose
and *generally* vote Republican, since their stupidity is usually much
less dangerous and always less persistent than the stupidity of the
Democrats. (This does not preclude voting for a Joe Lieberman in races
where the choice is between a sane relatively moral Democrat and a
left-wing whack job.)

